    <h2>1. Understanding Mixer Types: Spiral, Planetary, and Fork</h2>
    <p>Before diving into prices, it's important to understand the fundamental difference between the three dough mixer types. Each uses a completely different mixing action, and each produces a different result in the dough. Choosing the wrong type won't just frustrate you — it will produce inferior dough that no amount of skill can compensate for.</p>

    <h3>The Core Difference: How Each Mixer Works</h3>
    <p>A <strong>planetary mixer</strong> has a stationary bowl and a mixing attachment that orbits around the bowl while rotating on its own axis — like a planet around the sun, hence the name. The attachment moves through all parts of the bowl. It's the most versatile mixer, handling everything from whipping cream to mixing cookie dough, but it's not ideal for heavy bread doughs because the attachment passes through the dough repeatedly, generating significant heat from friction.</p>

    <p>A <strong>spiral mixer</strong> has a rotating bowl and a fixed spiral hook that stays in one position. The dough comes to the hook as the bowl rotates. The spiral hook works the dough with an efficient kneading action that develops gluten quickly with minimal heat generation. This is the standard machine for bread dough in commercial bakeries worldwide — efficient, relatively gentle on the dough temperature, and purpose-built for the job.</p>

    <p>A <strong>fork mixer</strong> has a fixed bowl and a fork-shaped tool that mimics the hand-kneading action of a baker — lifting, folding, and pushing the dough rather than churning it. Fork mixers develop gluten very slowly and gently, keeping the dough cold and well-oxygenated. The result is a more extensible, delicate dough with better fermentation characteristics — exactly what artisan bread bakers want. Fork mixers are slower and less common than spirals, but are preferred by serious artisan bakers worldwide.</p>

    <h2>2. Spiral Mixers: The Commercial Bread Baker's Workhorse</h2>
    <p>The spiral mixer is the most common dough mixer in Indian commercial bakeries. If you produce significant volumes of bread dough, pav dough, pizza dough, or any stiff-to-medium dough, a spiral mixer is almost certainly the right choice. Here's everything you need to know.</p>

    <h3>How Spiral Mixers Work</h3>
    <p>In a spiral mixer, the bowl rotates (usually at a fixed or two-speed rotation) while a fixed spiral hook sits in the dough and kneads it as the bowl brings the dough to the hook. The bowl also typically has a central dough divider that forces the dough under the hook for more efficient working. Most spiral mixers have two speeds — a slow first speed for initial incorporation and a faster second speed for full gluten development.</p>

    <p>The key advantage of a spiral mixer over a planetary mixer for bread dough is <strong>dough temperature control</strong>. The kneading action of a spiral mixer generates significantly less heat than the action of a planetary mixer, keeping the dough cooler. Warmer dough ferments faster and can result in overproofing or uneven fermentation. In commercial bread production, controlling dough temperature is critical, and spiral mixers are much better at this than planetary mixers.</p>

    <h3>Spiral Mixer Capacity: Understanding Kg Ratings</h3>
    <p>Spiral mixers are rated in kg of dough capacity, not litres of bowl volume. This is because dough weight is the practical unit that matters — you're measuring flour and water by weight. A 20kg spiral mixer can handle 20kg of dough per batch. For bread doughs (which are typically 60–70% hydration), 20kg of dough comes from roughly 12kg of flour plus 8kg of water.</p>

    <p>The rated capacity assumes standard bread dough at around 60% hydration. High-hydration doughs (70%+, like ciabatta or sourdough) will occupy more volume per kg, so you'll need to load slightly less. Very stiff doughs (like certain rye breads or some biscuit doughs) can sometimes be loaded above the rated kg capacity, but this strains the motor and should be avoided.</p>

