    <h2>6. Litres vs Kg Capacity Explained</h2>
    <p>One of the most common sources of confusion when buying a commercial dough mixer in India is the mismatch between how different mixer types rate their capacity. Planetary mixers use litres; spiral and fork mixers use kg. This section explains how to translate between them and choose the right capacity for your production needs.</p>

    <h3>Why the Different Rating Systems?</h3>
    <p>Planetary mixers use litres because they handle such a wide variety of products — from light whipped cream to dense dough — that dough weight alone wouldn't describe their full capability. The bowl volume is the common unit that applies across all applications.</p>
    <p>Spiral and fork mixers use kg because they only handle dough, and the batch size in production is always measured in weight (you're scaling recipes by flour weight, not volume). The kg rating tells you exactly how much finished dough comes out per batch.</p>

    <h3>Converting for Comparison</h3>
    <p>When comparing a planetary and a spiral mixer for dough work, use this rough conversion: <strong>1 kg of dough occupies approximately 1.2–1.5 litres of bowl space</strong>. So a 20L planetary mixer bowl can handle roughly 12–15 kg of dough (at maximum load). A 20 kg spiral mixer is rated specifically for 20 kg of dough and handles it with less stress on the motor.</p>

    <p>In practice: if you need to mix 15 kg of bread dough per batch, a 20 kg spiral mixer is the right choice. A 20L planetary mixer will struggle with 15 kg of stiff dough and will degrade quickly with regular use at that load. A 30L planetary could do it but costs significantly more and is oversized for everything else.</p>

    <h3>How Much Capacity Do You Actually Need?</h3>
    <p>Work backwards from your daily production target:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Calculate daily dough weight.</strong> If you make 100 loaves of 500g each, that's 50 kg of baked bread. Dough weighs about 20% more than baked bread (water evaporates during baking), so you need roughly 60 kg of dough per day.</li>
      <li><strong>Divide by batch size.</strong> If you mix in 15 kg batches, that's 4 batches. A 20 kg spiral mixer handles this with one batch in reserve.</li>
      <li><strong>Add capacity buffer.</strong> Buy 25–30% more capacity than your current needs. Businesses grow, and a mixer that's working at 95% of rated capacity every day will fail much sooner than one working at 70%.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>7. Indian Brands vs Imported Brands: Honest Assessment</h2>

    <h3>The Case for Indian Brands</h3>
    <p>Indian-manufactured spiral and planetary mixers have improved significantly in quality over the past decade. For bakeries that run 4–8 hours/day and have a service centre within reasonable distance, Indian brands offer excellent value. The cost difference is substantial — an Indian 20 kg spiral mixer costs ₹90,000–₹1,50,000 vs ₹1,50,000–₹2,20,000 for a comparable Italian or Taiwanese model. That ₹60,000–₹70,000 saving matters when you're fitting out a new bakery.</p>

    <p>Brands like Genius Baking Equipment and Ekon have built reasonable reputations in the Indian market. For small to medium bakeries on tighter budgets, they're a sensible choice provided you've verified local service availability.</p>

    <h3>The Case for Imported Brands</h3>
    <p>Imported mixers (Italian, German, Taiwanese) are built for 10–16 hours/day commercial operation. The build quality, motor protection, safety systems, and component quality are typically a tier above Indian brands at equivalent price points. For a bakery running heavy production every day, the total cost of ownership over 8–10 years often favours the imported brand despite the higher upfront cost — fewer breakdowns, lower maintenance costs, and a longer productive life.</p>

    <p>The other key advantage of established imported brands is parts availability and technical support. Italian brands like Famag have authorised service agents in major Indian cities. Spare parts for major brands are typically available within 3–7 days even in tier-2 cities. For a lesser-known Indian brand, parts availability can be uncertain and downtime costly.</p>

