    <h2>9. Buying Tips: What to Check Before You Purchase</h2>

    <h3>Motor Power and Protection</h3>
    <p>For spiral mixers, look for at least 1.5 HP (1.1 kW) for a 10 kg machine, 3 HP for 20 kg, and 5 HP for 30–40 kg. Machines with undersized motors will overheat during heavy dough mixing and fail prematurely. Check whether the motor has thermal overload protection — this is a basic safety feature that cuts power if the motor overheats. Better machines have automatic restart after cooling; cheaper ones require a manual reset.</p>

    <h3>Bowl Material and Construction</h3>
    <p>Commercial mixer bowls should be 304 food-grade stainless steel, minimum 1.2mm thickness. Thinner bowls dent, warp, and are harder to clean. The bowl attachment mechanism (the lock that keeps the bowl in place during operation) should be positive-locking — it shouldn't be possible for the bowl to rotate or lift during heavy mixing. Check this physically before purchasing.</p>

    <h3>Speed Options</h3>
    <p>For spiral mixers, two speeds are the commercial minimum — slow for incorporation and fast for gluten development. Three-speed models offer more control but aren't essential. For planetary mixers, variable speed (or at minimum three speeds) is strongly preferred for a commercial machine. Single-speed planetary mixers are consumer-grade and not suitable for commercial bakery use.</p>

    <h3>Safety Guards</h3>
    <p>The mixing bowl guard (the screen or cage over the open bowl top) is a critical safety feature. In India, some budget models omit this to reduce cost. This is a serious hazard — do not buy a commercial mixer without a proper bowl guard. Many states' FSSAI inspections will flag a missing bowl guard as a violation.</p>

    <h3>Voltage and Phase</h3>
    <p>Small mixers (under 10L planetary, under 10kg spiral) typically run on single-phase 230V power — standard in Indian homes and small shops. Larger commercial mixers require three-phase 415V power. Check your electrical supply before ordering. Installing three-phase power if you don't have it costs ₹15,000–₹40,000 depending on your location and connection type.</p>

    <h3>Warranty and Service</h3>
    <p>Minimum acceptable warranty for a commercial mixer is 12 months on parts and labour. Leading brands offer 18–24 months. More important than the warranty period is the service network — can they send a technician to your location within 48–72 hours of a breakdown call? Ask the dealer specifically: where is the nearest service centre? What's the typical response time? What's the availability of critical spare parts (motor, gearbox)?</p>

    <h2>10. Total Cost of Ownership: Beyond the Purchase Price</h2>
    <p>The purchase price is only part of the true cost of a commercial dough mixer. For a machine you'll run 8+ hours/day for 10+ years, the total cost of ownership calculation matters.</p>

    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Cost Component</th><th>Budget Indian Brand (20kg Spiral)</th><th>Mid-Range Imported (20kg Spiral)</th></tr></thead>
