        <tr><td>Annual maintenance cost</td><td>₹15,000–₹25,000</td><td>₹8,000–₹15,000</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Expected service life</td><td>5–7 years</td><td>10–15 years</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Total maintenance (full life)</td><td>₹90,000–₹1,75,000</td><td>₹80,000–₹2,25,000</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Downtime cost (breakdowns)</td><td>Higher (2–4 incidents/year)</td><td>Lower (0–1 incidents/year)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Total cost of ownership (10yr)</td><td>₹2,90,000–₹3,75,000</td><td>₹2,60,000–₹4,05,000</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>The gap narrows significantly when you factor in the higher maintenance costs and shorter service life of budget equipment. For high-use applications (8+ hours/day), the imported mixer often wins on total cost of ownership despite the higher purchase price.</p>

    <!-- FAQ -->
    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is the price of a commercial dough mixer in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Commercial dough mixer prices in India in 2026 range from ₹25,000 for a small 5-litre planetary mixer (Indian brand) to over ₹6 lakh for a large 100 kg Italian fork mixer. The most common commercial range for small-medium Indian bakeries is ₹80,000–₹2,50,000 for a 10–30 kg spiral mixer from an Indian or Taiwanese brand. Professional imported spiral mixers (Italian, German) for the same capacity cost ₹1,50,000–₹3,50,000.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Which is better for bread dough — spiral or planetary mixer? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">For bread dough, a spiral mixer is almost always better than a planetary mixer. Spiral mixers develop gluten more efficiently, generate less heat during mixing (critical for fermentation control), and handle larger batches more effectively. A planetary mixer with a dough hook can make bread dough but is not designed for heavy commercial bread production — the motor and gearbox will wear faster, and dough temperature will be higher. Use a planetary for cakes, icings, pastry, and light doughs; use a spiral for bread, pizza, and other substantial doughs.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What capacity spiral mixer do I need for a small bakery? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">For a small bakery producing 50–150 loaves per day (25–75 kg of baked bread), a 10–20 kg spiral mixer is usually appropriate. A 10 kg spiral mixer can process roughly 80–120 kg of dough per day in 8–12 batches; a 20 kg spiral can do 160–240 kg/day. Always buy with room for growth — a 20 kg machine at 60% utilisation will last much longer than a 10 kg machine at 90% utilisation. Most small Indian commercial bakeries find a 20 kg spiral mixer to be the sweet spot.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is the difference between a planetary mixer and a spiral mixer? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">A planetary mixer has a stationary bowl and a rotating attachment that orbits around the bowl, making it versatile for many products (cakes, creams, cookies, soft doughs). A spiral mixer has a rotating bowl and a fixed spiral hook — it's purpose-built for bread and pizza dough, developing gluten efficiently with less heat generation. Planetary mixers are rated in litres; spiral mixers in kg. For a bakery that makes both bread and pastries, most operations need one of each.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is a fork mixer and do I need one? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">A fork mixer is a specialised dough mixer that uses a fork-shaped tool to mimic hand-kneading — lifting and folding the dough rather than churning it. It develops gluten very slowly and gently, keeping dough temperature low and producing highly extensible, well-oxygenated dough. Fork mixers are the preferred choice for serious artisan bakers producing high-hydration sourdoughs, baguettes, and ciabatta at scale. They're predominantly made in Italy and cost significantly more than spiral mixers. Most standard Indian commercial bakeries producing sandwich bread, pav, or pizza don't need a fork mixer. Artisan bakeries targeting premium markets should seriously consider one.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Which dough mixer brands are best in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">For spiral mixers: Italian brands (Famag, VMI, Bernardi) for premium artisan use; Sinmag (Taiwan) for excellent mid-range value; Genius and Ekon (Indian) for budget commercial use. For planetary mixers: Hobart and Electrolux Professional for premium hotel/high-volume use; Sinmag for solid mid-range; Genius and Maharaja Commercial for budget small-bakery use. For fork mixers: Famag and Bernardi (Italian) are the leading options available in India. When choosing a brand, always verify that service support and spare parts are available in your city before purchasing.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Can I use a planetary mixer for roti or chapati dough? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">A planetary mixer with a dough hook can mix roti/chapati dough, but it's not the ideal tool. Roti dough is relatively stiff and requires significant kneading to achieve the right texture. For small batches (under 3 kg), a planetary mixer works adequately. For larger production, a spiral mixer is better — more efficient, less heat, and less wear on the machine. For very high-volume roti production, dedicated dough kneading machines designed specifically for Indian flatbread doughs (available from ₹60,000–₹3,50,000) are the most efficient option.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Should I buy Indian or imported dough mixer for my bakery? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">It depends on your usage intensity and budget. For bakeries running less than 6 hours/day with modest production, a good Indian brand mixer offers excellent value. For bakeries running 8–16 hours/day in commercial production, the higher quality, longer service life, and better motor protection of imported brands (Italian, Taiwanese) typically justifies the 50–100% price premium. Always factor in service availability in your location — a premium imported brand with no local service is worse than a budget Indian brand with a technician an hour away. If budget allows, Sinmag (Taiwanese) offers a good balance of quality, price, and service availability for most Indian commercial bakeries.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

